<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Threatens to Reject Peace Process Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein, the political wing of
the Irish Republican Army (IRA), warned Britain on Saturday not to
halt the early release of jailed republican guerrillas in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein's chief negotiator Martin McGuinness told BBC radio
that any suspension of the release would be a "serious mistake"
that could affect whether they take part in the review of the Good
Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
He said it was far from certain Sinn Fein would take part in
the peace process review and that stopping prisoner releases would
throw its participation further into question.
</P>
<P>
"I think that any sanction on the prisoners, coming on top of
all of that, could have very serious repercussions for Sinn Fein's
participation in any review," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mo Mowlam, Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary, hinted on
Friday she might suspend the early release of guerrilla prisoners
if she decided that the IRA had broken its two-year-old ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
But Mowlam signalled she would not expel Sinn Fein from next
month's review of the "Good Friday" accord even if she decided
that the IRA had broken the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The IRA truce has been questioned following the murder of a
taxi driver in Belfast last month.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam has received security briefings on the incidents and is
expected to give her verdict in the coming week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
