<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Raises Gasoline Price Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese government Saturday
imposed a price hike on gasoline in view of rising international
oil prices, the third time in four months.
</P>
<P>
The price hike amounts to 300 Lebanese pounds (about 20
U.S. cents) per 20 liters of gasoline, the Voice of the People
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The new hike brought the prices up to 13,200 pounds (about 8.8
dollars) for 20 liters of unleaded or 98 Octane gasoline, with
regular going up to 12,900 pounds (about 8.6 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Oil Minister Suleiman Traboulsi told the radio that without
such a price rise, the government would lose 13 billion pounds
(about 8.67 million dollars) a week in revenue due to rising oil
prices on the world market.
</P>
<P>
The government had imposed a 400-pound (about 27 cents) hike on
gasoline prices last Thursday, in addition to tacking on a charge
of 1,000 pounds (about 67 cents) on each 10 kilograms of butane.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government funds accrued from a 2,000-
pound (about 1.33 dollars) surtax on oil prices in April have
already been eaten up by increasing oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The increase has triggered outcries from consumers, who said
they could not afford the extra charges as the country is in an
economic recession.
</P>
<P>
In the streets in Beirut, gas stations claimed that they
had run out of supplies as fuel distributors have reportedly
refused supply in protest against the increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
