<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Girl Rescued After Being Trapped for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A nine-year-old Israeli girl
was rescued Saturday from the rubble of a building in Turkey that
collapsed more than four days ago in a devastating earthquake,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Shiran Franco was flown home for medical treatment hours after
she was dug out at about 4 a.m. (0100 GMT) Saturday by an Israeli
army rescue team in the town of Cinarcik, 50 kilometers south of
Istanbul, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Doctors described her general condition as "good" except
suffering from dehydration. She will be relieved from hospital in
about two or three days, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Franco and her family were vacationing in Cinarcik when the
apartment they stayed in was toppled by the shattering
earthquake, which has killed more than 10,000 people so far.
</P>
<P>
Franco's mother managed to escape from the flattened building
30 hours after it collapsed. The body of Franco's twin brother,
Arye, was found Saturday, and her father and grandparents are
still missing.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli army rescue team searching for the Franco family
had almost given up hope until they heard her call for help. It
took the rescuers only an hour to free her from the ruins.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers who rescued Franco almost burst into tears when
she spoke to them, according to a special film broadcasting on
Israel's Channel One.
</P>
<P>
Besides emergency supplies, Israel has sent more than 380
rescue workers and doctors as well as sniffer dogs to Turkey to
help in the search for survivors.
</P>
<P>
It also set up a field hospital that is equipped with an
intensive-care unit and a 100-bed ward. Two babies were born in
the hospital, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli team has rescued seven people alive and found 72
bodies, the radio said. Among the 14 Israelis who were trapped in
collapsed buildings, six were rescued alive, five confirmed dead
and three still missing.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which keeps close ties with Israel, is also a popular
holiday destination for Israelis. All the 14 Israelis went to
Turkey for vacationing, the radio said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
