<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Customs Reports on Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran's imports volume last
Iranian year (ending March 20, 1999) reached 14 billion
U.S. dollars and that of exports of non-oil goods 3 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figures, contained in a two-volume yearbook of statistics
on Iran's foreign trade, showed that the country's oil export
earnings last year were estimated at 14 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the yearbook released by the Customs
Administration on Saturday, Iran imported intermediary goods worth
6 billion dollars, capital goods worth 6 billion dollars and
consumer goods worth 2 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
In the exporting sector, industrial goods accounted for 32.1
percent of the volume, worth 969 million dollars, followed by
agricultural products, 613 million dollars; carpets and
handicrafts, 549 million dollars and mineral products, 210
million dollars, the statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
Iran's economy was severely affected by low prices of oil, its
prime foreign exchange earner. To clamp down on inflation, the
country has been promoting export of non-oil commodities and at
the same time trying to limit import of non-essential goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
