<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Taiwan Is Inseparable Part of China:" Seminar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- "Everyone knows that there is only
one China in the world, the government of the People's Republic of
China is the sole legitimate government representing the whole of
China, and that Taiwan is an inseparable part of the Chinese
territory," a speaker told a seminar here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Solving the Taiwan issue and reunifying the motherland is the
common aspiration of all Chinese people," Engineer F.R. Siddiqui,
president of the Bangladesh-China Cultural, Economic and Mass
Communication Center (BCCEMCC), told the seminar on "Peaceful
Reunification of Taiwan to the Motherland."
</P>
<P>
The seminar was organized by the BCCEMCC and was attended by
some 80 scholars, diplomats, politicians and dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
Lee Teng-hui's remarks and attempts to separate China received
strong condemnation by all the Chinese, including the Taiwan
compatriots and the people of Chinese origin in other parts of the
world, and met with objection from the international community as
well, he said.
</P>
<P>
China is continuing to gain greater international status, and
the United Nations and the great majority of the countries in the
world now recognize that there is only one China and Taiwan is
part of Chinese territory, he said.
</P>
<P>
Though the two sides of the Taiwan Straits have remained in a
state of separation for 50 years, history and reality have proved
that the "two states" statement by Lee Teng-hui is absurd,
Siddiqui observed.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leadership have made unremitting efforts to
seriously implement the policies of "peaceful reunification" and
"one country, two systems," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
There is only one China in the world and the status of Taiwan
as a part of China remains unchanged, he said. "China's
sovereignty and territorial integrity brook no separation."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Steps Up Environment Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
taken a series of steps to protect the environment, check
pollution and conserve the country's cultural heritage, the
minister of state for population and environment told parliament
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Bhakta B. Balayar said the government has realized the need to
maintain environmental balance while carrying out development
activities so as to achieve sustainable development goals.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has adopted the policy of integrating
the concept of environmental conservation in various sectoral
development programs.
</P>
<P>
Balayar said that to preserve the historical and archaeological
heritage and improve the environment and public health conditions
in Kathmandu Valley, the government has decided to provide
three-wheeler owners a 75 percent customs discount on importing
micro buses in order to help ban the polluting vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The government has also increased customs duties on the import
of used and reconditioned vehicles and taken efforts to install
treatment plants for industrial waste and reduce polluting
factors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Various programs have been launched through a number of
non-governmental organizations (NGO) for soil conservation,
building green parks and conservation of the sources of water, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government is providing necessary support to NGOs for
recycling solid waste and producing organic fertilizers of the
waste, he said, adding that an agreement has been signed between
the governments of Nepal and Denmark on implementation of various
environment protection projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
