<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL -- Blaze in a refinery in western Turkey has been
under control after the strong efforts made by foreign rescue
experts, a Turkish official said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish private NTV quoted Ismail Alakoc, the chairman of the
boarding committee of Turkish Petrol Refineries Company as saying
that the strong fire of the Izmit Refinery in Kocaeli province
caused by Tuesday's monster earthquake has been under control with
the help of foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Azerbaijan, Greece, France, the Netherlands,
Kazakistan, Ukraine and Russia have been participating in the
fight against the blaze that threatened to engulf the entire field
of 30 storage tanks containing 1 million tons of crude
oil. (BC-Turkey-Refinery)
</P>
<P>
ISTANBUL -- Turkish monster earthquake measuring 7.4 on the
Richter scale has caused about 20 billion U.S. dollars in economic
loss, accounting for half of the country's budget in 1999, Turkish
experts has said here.
</P>
<P>
Local private NTV Saturday quoted the experts as saying that
the economic loss caused by the killer earthquake also accounts
for half of Turkey's domestic debt of 40 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures, at least 10,059 people have
been killed, 45,000 others injured in the quake which was one of
the largest in this century in Turkey. (BC-Turkey-Economic Loss)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Saturday rejected claims by Argentine Vice
President Carlos Ruckauf that its diplomats had been involved in a
bombing attack on a Jewish center in Buenos Aires five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid-Reza Asefi dismissed the
accusations as "unfounded," saying Ruckauf's "repeated,
undocumented and irresponsible claims were aimed at creating
ballyhoo against Iran."
</P>
<P>
Iran's cultural attache to Argentina was accused of being
involved in the bomb explosion in 1994 which killed 88 people and
injured 159 others. (BC-Iran-Argentina-Bombing)
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has pledged that the
U.S. would continue to promote a solution to the Cyprus issue
based on a bizonal, bicommunal federation, the Cyprus News Agency
(CNA) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In his bi-monthly report to the U.S. Congress on the Cyprus
issue, Clinton recalled that during NATO's Washington summit on
the 50th anniversary of the military bloc, he "met with Turkish
President Suleyman Demirel and Greek Premier Constantinos Simitis
to underscore the importance of a just and lasting solution for
all Cypriots." (BC-Cyprus-US)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A nine-year-old Israeli girl was rescued Saturday
from the rubble of a building in Turkey that collapsed more than
four days ago in a devastating earthquake, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Shiran Franco was flown home for medical treatment hours after
she was dug out at about 4 a.m. (0100 GMT) Saturday by an Israeli
army rescue team in the town of Cinarcik, 50 kilometers south of
Istanbul, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Doctors described her general condition as "good" except
suffering from dehydration. She will be relieved from hospital in
about two or three days, the radio said.
(BC-Israel-Turkey-Quake)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Defense Ministry and Armed Forces Logistics
issued a statement here Saturday, dismissing a Turkish newspaper
report that Iran intends to carry out nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Iran fully adheres to the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT)
on nuclear weapons, and all its atomic programs are based on
"peaceful use of nuclear energy for medical, agricultural and
energy-generation purposes" and "within the framework of
the internationally-recognized absolute rights of any country."
</P>
<P>
Tehran has been accused by the U.S. of being ambitious in
pursuing non-conventional weapons capabilities, a charge which
Iran has repeatedly denied. (BC-Iran-Denial-Nuclear) 
</P>
