<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Chief of Museum Detained for Missing Ancient Tablets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The former manager of the Museum
of Ancient Iran was detained for the disappearance of two ancient
golden and silver tablets, the Persian-language daily "Iran"
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A court ordered Tehrani Moqoddam to be temporarily detained as
investigation continues into the loss of the invaluable tablets,
which has led to the arrest of an archaeologist who knew about the
last place where the tablets were kept.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the loss of the tablets was made known
to officials only when the Cultural Heritage Organization decided
to hold an exhibition of ancient Iranian tablets. Moqoddam was
then summoned to the court and questioned.
</P>
<P>
An informed source told the daily that some newspapers in 1995
had run stories on the disappearance of the tablets, but Moqaddam
had refused to take any measures or report it to officials
responsible. This persuaded the court to issue a warrant for his
arrest.
</P>
<P>
The two identical precious tablets date back to more than
3,000 years ago. They were discovered during excavation
operations in the Persepolis historical site near the southern
city of Shiraz about 60 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
