<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Life Returns to Normal in Quake-Stricken </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, August 21 (Xinhua) -- As anguished families bury
their loved ones who perished in the strong earthquake striking
northwestern Turkey Tuesday morning, life in most parts of the
quake-hit Istanbul, the largest city of the country, has virtually
returned to normal by Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Communication, electricity and water supplies, which were cut
off in the metropolis straddling Europe and Asia by the pre-dawn
catastrophe, resumed later Tuesday in many parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
And since Wednesday, the vast majority of the 12 million
Istanbul residents are having their telephone lines, electric
lights and running water back in normal.
</P>
<P>
Aucilar, an outskirt in western Istanbul overseeing the
Marmara Sea, was the worst hit area of the city. While rescuers
were still digging in the debris of flattened buildings in search
for survivors and victims, power and water supplies there were
already rehabilitated Friday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the vibration which sent the whole city trembling for
45 seconds at 3:02 a.m. (0002 GMT) Tuesday with a magnitude of
7.4 degrees on the Richter scale, most buildings in central
Istanbul were unharmed.
</P>
<P>
Four days after the tremor, streets in Istanbul are already
back into their usual bustle. Department stores, supermarkets and
restaurants, which were not closed even Tuesday, are running
their normal time.
</P>
<P>
Financial institutions are among the sectors most
conspicuously affected by the quake. Many banks were closed due
to communication and power cut-offs, but most have already
resumed their business.
</P>
<P>
The Istanbul Stock Exchange, however, would not open until
next Monday after trading was intercepted by the quake since
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tourism, one of the pillars of Istanbul's economy, seemed to
have suffered no obvious backlashes from the quake. Key tourist
attractions in central Istanbul, such as the Church of St. Sophia
and the Mosque of Sultanahmet (widely known as the Blue Mosque),
remained intact.
</P>
<P>
The seismologic nightmare has so far killed over 900 people in
Istanbul itself, mostly in the low-income outskirts, like Aucilar
and Safakoy, where shoddy construction prevails.
</P>
<P>
In the Church of St. Sophia, a young woman from Hungary, who
arrived in Turkey two days ago with her parents, said she had
consulted with the Hungarian Consulate here before going on with
their original trip schedule, and "they said it wasn't very
dangerous."
</P>
<P>
"We came from the airport, we took the taxi, we didn't see
anything. We were actually very surprised because we had expected
it to be very bad," she said, adding her family would stay here
for another two days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
