<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Shot Dead in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Nine people were shot dead
in separate incidents for no apparent reasons in a farm near
KwaMashu north of Durban in KwaZulu-Natal overnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
The killed included a three-year-old boy who was brought to
hospital after being shot but died upon arrival.
</P>
<P>
Two shacks in the area were burnt down and the occupants were
burnt beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
A few weeks ago, three people were killed in the same area.
</P>
<P>
The massacre started around 11 p.m. (2100 GMT) on Friday when
attackers shot and killed two people outside their home in the
informal settlement, South African Press Association quoted a
police officer as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nearly an hour later two other people were shot and
subsequently died in a shack about 300 meters away from the first
attack.
</P>
<P>
Around 3 a.m. (0100 GMT) on Saturday a 51-year-old man and his
three sons were gunned down and their shack set on fire. A fifth
member of the family was taken to hospital in a critical
condition.
</P>
<P>
Police are investigating the incidents and at the moment they
could not say whether the killings were politically or criminally
motivated.
</P>
<P>
The police also issued a 250,000-rand (41,700 U.S. dollars)
reward for any information that leads to the arrest and conviction
of the attackers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Chief of Museum Detained for Missing Ancient Tablets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The former manager of the Museum
of Ancient Iran was detained for the disappearance of two ancient
golden and silver tablets, the Persian-language daily "Iran"
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A court ordered Tehrani Moqoddam to be temporarily detained as
investigation continues into the loss of the invaluable tablets,
which has led to the arrest of an archaeologist who knew about the
last place where the tablets were kept.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the loss of the tablets was made known
to officials only when the Cultural Heritage Organization decided
to hold an exhibition of ancient Iranian tablets. Moqoddam was
then summoned to the court and questioned.
</P>
<P>
An informed source told the daily that some newspapers in 1995
had run stories on the disappearance of the tablets, but Moqaddam
had refused to take any measures or report it to officials
responsible. This persuaded the court to issue a warrant for his
arrest.
</P>
<P>
The two identical precious tablets date back to more than
3,000 years ago. They were discovered during excavation
operations in the Persepolis historical site near the southern
city of Shiraz about 60 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Asks U.N. to Provide Emergency Help to Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Liberian Government said Saturday
that the country does not have the means to cope with the
worsening refugee flood issue from the fighting areas between
government troops and rebels and appealed to the international
community for help.
</P>
<P>
Liberian Information Minister Joe Mulbah said that the United
Nations should give his country urgent food and medical aid to
help tide off the worsening humanitarian emergency in the northern
part of the country, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Mulbah said towns in the fighting areas along the
Liberian-Guinean border towns were being burnt in "rampant acts
of arson" -- with thousands of civilians caught in the cross
fire, and an unknown number killed.
</P>
<P>
He said government forces were exerting "all efforts to stop
civilian casualties".
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR), which
says it hopes to be able to return to the area soon, pulled its
staff out of the region last week because of the security
situation and the taking of hostages by rebels.
</P>
<P>
A World Food Program official indicated today in Monrovia that
international aid organizations might not be able to provide
immediate relief to the remote-fighting region. Earlier this
week the government announced the capture of the towns of Foya,
Kolahun and Medekoma. But the government troops' further offensive
is believed to be difficult.
</P>
<P>
The fighting began last week when armed insurgents crossed into
Lofa County from neighboring Guinea. Liberian Government had
declared a state of emergency in the area and accused Guinea of
providing support for the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Guinean President Lansana Conte latter denied Liberia's charge
and accused the Liberian authorities of ingratitude toward his
country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Africa No 1 radio, Conte said, "Guinea continues to
give assistance and to harbor thousands of Liberian refugees."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
