<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chissano Urges Varsity graduates to Contribute to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano Saturday said the society expects more university
graduates to make contribution toward solving existing problems
and preventing future ones.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking in Maputo at the ceremony presenting with
diplomas 312 new graduates from the country's oldest higher
education institution, the Eduardo Mondlane University (UEM).
</P>
<P>
Chissano urge the university to maintain a constant link with
other levels of the national education system, so as to help solve
the multiple problems facing Mozambican education.
</P>
<P>
He stressed "the need for universities and other schools to
train productive citizens, people who produce goods an who produce
ideas, citizens with initiatives. Whoever is trained at the UEM
should leave with a spirit of enterprise."
</P>
<P>
Graduates, he added, should be trained not only to occupy jobs
"but above all to have the capacity to create employment for
themselves and for others".
</P>
<P>
Chissano added that teaching must be closely linked to
research, since " any self-respecting university must engage in
research."
</P>
<P>
He praise the UEM's efforts to introduce post-graduate courses,
saying that these would increase research capacity, with a
corresponding impact on the country's development, and an
improvement in teaching methods.
</P>
<P>
Chissano recognized that improving the university curriculum
and building up the research capacity, among others, would all
require major investment.
</P>
<P>
He urged the UEM to assist the state in carrying out this duty,
and warned that the university's administrative and financial
autonomy obliges it to introduce transparent and reliable forms of
management.
</P>
<P>
"Stringent measures must be introduced to hold back
expenditure, and to rationalize resources", he declared.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also criticized the gender imbalance among the new
graduates, 216 of whom are men, and only 96 women. He said the
university must work to mitigate this imbalance.
</P>
<P>
There is also an imbalance in the faculties from which the
students graduated. Social and human sciences contributed 153 of
the graduates, engineering and technology 58, biological sciences
49, agronomy and forestry 37, and natural sciences just 15.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997-98 academic year, the UEM graduated 243 students,
so there has been an increase in graduations of around 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the graduation rate remains shockingly low. There are
currently 6, 500 students, most of them on five year courses. One
might therefore reasonably expect 1,000 or so students to graduate
per year.
</P>
<P>
There are 811 full and part time teaching staff. In other
words, the UEM is alarmingly unproductive.
</P>
<P>
The blame for this undoubtedly lies in the system, inherited
from Portuguese colonialism, of a five year first degree known as
a " licenciatura". This supposedly lies somewhere between a
bachelors degree and a masters.
</P>
<P>
It involves writing a final dissertation, and many students
never finish this work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
