<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Minister of Energy Habibollah Bitaraf said on
Saturday that some 69 dams are now under construction in the
country and a number of them are due to go on stream by the year
end.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an inauguration ceremony for Shiyadh dam in Babol
in the Caspian province of Mazandaran, he said that construction
of 200 other dams are now under study.
</P>
<P>
"Some 71 dams have been constructed and put into operation in
the country so far," he added.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A permanent fair of Egyptian products will be held at
the Egyptian Trade Representation Office in Pretoria, South
Africa, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The products to be shown include carpets, wooden furniture,
ready-made clothes, textiles, leather, shoes, aluminium kitchen
utensils, ceramics and paints.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran produced over 65,000 washing machines in the
first four months of the year, 16 percent more than the same
period last year, said managing director of metals and casting
affairs of the Ministry of Industries Taqi Mousavi-Pour Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's washing machine production capacity is 1
million units annually but "due to the market saturation, the plan
is to produce only 300,000 units this year."
</P>
<P>
He added that the production of electric vacuums reached
148,000 units, 48 percent higher than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months, 330,000 refrigerators and freezers
were produced, six percent lower than a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will take part in the Zagreb International
Autumn Fair to be held in mid-September in Croatia, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources at the Croatian Embassy in Cairo said this
is an important step in promoting trade cooperation between the
two countries and an opportunity to show Egyptian products in
Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The sources said a large Egyptian businessmen delegation is to
visit Croatia during the fair, which they said will provide an
opportunity for businessmen of the two countries to seek ways of
enhancing trade cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Tourism Has Bright Future: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Second Deputy Premier
and Minister of Tourism, Trade and Industry Moses Ali has assured
Ugandans that the country's tourism industry has a bright future.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when meeting with local officials in
northeastern Uganda on the proposals made by the protected areas
assessment program Saturday, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
The program is charged with reviewing the status of wildlife
protected areas throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that the government is anxious to save
the more important wildlife parks, reserves and to rebuild tourist
facilities so that Uganda attracts more foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed claims that the government has intentions to
take land in Karimoja in form of gazetting it as wildlife
reserves.
</P>
<P>
The protected area plan, which was completed in March this
year, highlights those areas of high biological diversity which
should be protected in parks and reserves.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's tourism industry suffered a heavy blow in early March
when eight foreign tourists were killed in a forest park in
western Uganda. The incident was immediately followed by a spate
of mass trip cancellations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
