<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African FM Tours Uganda, Rwanda for Congo Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Nkosazana Zuma left for Uganda and Rwanda Saturday for a
new round of talks on the long-running conflict in the Democratic
Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Zuma's latest peace mission may also include a stopover in the
Congo, her spokesman Vincent Hlongwane said.
</P>
<P>
Zuma is scheduled to meet Ugandan government officials in
Kampala Saturday and hold talks with Rwandan officials in Kigali
Sunday, Hlongwane said.
</P>
<P>
Depending on the outcome of these meetings she may travel to
Goma, the rebel stronghold close to the Rwandan border in eastern
Congo, for talks with representatives of the divided Congolese
Rally for Democracy (CRD).
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda back different factions of the CRD, the main
rebel movement fighting to overthrow President Laurent Kabila and
the only party to the conflict which did not sign a cease-fire
agreement in Lusaka on July 10.
</P>
<P>
They failed to do so because of a disagreement over which
faction of the CRD should sign the accord. The most powerful
faction, backed by Rwanda and led by Emile Ilunga, is based in
Goma.
</P>
<P>
Zuma's latest peace shuttle follows discussions on the Congo at
the summit of the 14-nation Southern African Development Community
(SADC) in Maputo this week and is part of regional efforts to
ensure that the rebels sign the Lusaka cease-fire, Hlongwane said.
</P>
<P>
She was in Kisangani, the third largest city in northeastern
Congo which has been divided into two by the rebel factions, a
fortnight ago in an attempt to establish which is the "legitimate
CRD" and hence entitled to sign the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Kisangani is the main base of the second, smaller faction of
the CRD backed by Uganda and led by Ernest Wamba dia Wamba.
</P>
<P>
After Zuma's visit, fighting erupted in Kisangani between
Rwandan and Ugandan soldiers, leaving 200 dead and 50 injured.
</P>
<P>
Calm has since returned to the area thanks to a joint
cease-fire declaration by Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and
Rwandan vice-president Paul Kagame.
</P>
<P>
Zuma will be accompanied by several South African officials,
including an advisor in President Thabo Mbeki's office, the
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
He said the delegation will consist exclusively of South
Africans, and it will not be a joint mission by South Africa and
Zambia, as the visit to Kisangani was.
</P>
<P>
Zuma was accompanied to Kisangani by the Zambian Minister of
Presidential Affairs, Eric Silwamba, and declared afterwards that
the onus was on Zambia to establish which CRD faction should sign
the accord, as that country was leading the Congo peace process.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear how long Zuma will stay in central Africa this
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Deplores Immorality In Women's League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President and First
Secretary of the ruling Zanu (PF) party Robert Mugabe has
condemned immoral behavior among some members of the Women's
League and emphasized that party members, especially men in top
party positions should refrain from being destructive to the
party.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who officially closed the two-day third National
Women's League Conference in Harare Saturday, said there was need
to strengthen ties in all provinces and cooperation with leaders
in terms of policy and correct guidance.
</P>
<P>
He repeatedly reiterated the need for party unity.
</P>
<P>
"There have been rumors and talk about some of your members who
are of loose morals and have gone to the extend of destroying
other people's families," he said.
</P>
<P>
Congratulating the newly appointed 26-member executive of the
Women's League, he said they should use their new posts to the
advantage and benefit of the people and not just hold on to them.
</P>
<P>
"Give new light in your respective provinces and the country as
a whole and there must never be any division," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe also encouraged the women to meet and correct the gap
that has been created in the new executive following none
representation of an executive member in the new committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stepashin Shuns New Right-Centrist Bloc </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia's former prime minister
Sergei Stepashin on Saturday refused to join two other former
premiers in a new pro-Kremlin, right-centrist political bloc.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, who was fired as prime minister earlier this month,
has been consulting with parties led by two other ex-premiers:
Viktor Chernomyrdin's Our Home is Russia and Sergei Kiriyenko's
New Force.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to media reports late Friday that the three former
prime ministers would form a coalition, Stepashin announced
Saturday that he would stay out and instead start to run for the
State Duma, or lower house of parliament, in a constituency in his
hometown of St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
"You cannot bring together people who do not fit together,"
Stepashin said. "There are too many ambitions."
</P>
<P>
"I want to be honest with myself and the people, without
deceit, without betraying my ideals," the Interfax news agency
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Kremlin had apparently been hoping the ex-premiers' bloc
would counter the coalition of Fatherland-All Russia, led by
Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov and another former prime minister,
Yevgeny Primakov.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- An earthquake occurred in southeastern Turkey on
Sunday afternoon, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake with a preliminary magnitude of 4.3 struck
southeastern province of Elazig at 14:13 p.m local time (11:13 GMT)
, but no serious damage or injuries from the jolt were reported.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake was about 600 kilometers east of
Ankara, capital of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The monster earthquake measuring 7.4 on the Richter scale hit
western Turkey in the early hours of August 17 and killed over 12,
000 people and injured over 33,000 others in the region. (Turkey-
Quake)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Two Israeli soldiers were wounded by mortar fire
early Sunday in a buffer zone set up by Israel in south Lebanon,
Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that one of them was hurt lightly, and another
suffered from medial injury.
</P>
<P>
The two soldiers were wounded at an army post in the eastern
sector of the buffer zone established by Israel in 1985 in south
Lebanon with a claimed aim of preventing its northern borders from
attacks by Lebanese guerrillas .
</P>
<P>
The report said that it was the Hezbollah group which launched
the attack.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, Israeli troops returned cannon fire.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah has been the most active militant group in south
Lebanon fighting to oust Israeli troops from Lebanon. (Israel-
Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- A total of 11 rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) have been killed in recent military operations in
southeastern Turkey, an official statement said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by the office of the Emergency Regional
Rule, said that the Turkish security forces had wiped out seven
PKK rebels in armed clashes in Zori region in Batman province,two
in Tunceli province and two in the provinces of Diyarbakir and
Sirnak.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the security forces captured four PKK militants in
the provinces of Diyarbakir and Sirnak and two PKK guerrillas
surrendered to the security forces in Bingol province.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey, which has claimed over 37,
000 lives in conflicts between the security forces and the PKK. (
Turkey-PKK)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- A China Airlines jet caught fire while landing at
Hong Kong International Airport in a tropical storm Sunday evening,
killing two and injuring at least 212 of the 315 people on board,
according to the Hong Kong Hospital Authority.
</P>
<P>
The China Airlines MD-11 passenger plane carrying 315 people,
including 15 crew members, caught fire at 6:45 p.m. when it landed
at the airport amid a fierce storm.
</P>
<P>
The airliner, Flight CI-642, was flying from Bangkok to Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Two passengers, who witnessed the accident, said that there was
no explosion on the plane, but a fire ball could be seen coming up.
</P>
<P>
Most of the passengers were Thais and Portuguese. (China-HK-
Plane-Fire) 
</P>
</TEXT>
