<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Song of Life: Story of National Anthem Conductor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: This year is the 50th anniversary of the People'
s Republic of China. Xinhua News Agency will release a series of
50 stories on Chinese men and women, young and old, to present a
picture of the changes that have taken place in China over the
past 50 years. These different people will describe their own
experiences and how they fit into the changes in the motherland.
This is the first article.
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The scene is forever fixed in
Luo Lang's memory of the day he conducted a military band playing
the National Anthem of the People's Republic China.
</P>
<P>
Tian'anmen Square was calm and a breeze was blowing in the
gentle autumn sunshine that afternoon on October 1, 1949 and,
suddenly, music rent the sky. The music was being played by a 200-
member band and a red flag was being raised and a 56-gun salute
went off.
</P>
<P>
Luo was 29. The whole square was jolted at that extraordinary
moment and it was an unforgettable splendor, he told Xinhua
recently, waving arms and humming the National Anthem in his house
in Beijing. That afternoon, Mao Zedong declared the founding of
the People's Republic, opening an brand new chapter in the history
of the 5,000-year-old country.
</P>
<P>
Luo was born in Fujian province and moved to Malaysia with his
family when he was 9, and, when Japanese troops attacked Shanghai
on September 13, 1937, he was in primary school. The news arrived
when he was on his way to school. A thousand Chinese in the small
Malaysian town rushed out, shouting and crying, and school
suspended class.
</P>
<P>
His father drew a picture of a dark future to him saying that
China was going to be conquered by the Japanese and that all
Chinese would become slaves.
</P>
<P>
Luo returned to China a few years later and heard a song titled
"March of The Militia" for the first time. It later became the
national anthem. He says he was surprisingly moved by it because
it expressed the nation's resolve to fight to the death.
</P>
<P>
Luo went to Yan'an singing the song and became an army musician
after studying at a Communist arts academy. He says he can not
remember how many times he has conducted orchestras playing the
song, but can only remember just how China changed from a dying
nation into a powerful one.
</P>
<P>
The biggest changes took place after 1949. When he went back to
his small hometown in Fujian one day, he could not recognize it.
The farmland of 50 years ago has been replaced by highways and
skyscrapers. No one could imagine the place during wartime.
</P>
<P>
And, his small army band in Yan'an has become a very big one
and the members are always proud to play the national anthems for
visiting dignitaries. Fifty years ago they had rough instruments
captured from the enemy, but today they have state-of-the-art
Chinese equipment.
</P>
<P>
Remarkable changes have also taken place in the 70-year-old Luo.
He bought a computer and spent all day studying the mysteriously
new Windows 98 and says he is looking forward to sending e-mail to
old friends. But the sound of the national anthem brings him back
to reality from cyberspace. "It's the music of my soul and the
song of my life," he says in a firm voice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Temporary Settlement Areas to be Formed for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Public Works and Housing
Minister Koray Aydin said here on Sunday that temporary
settlement areas that are close to their former houses will be
formed for the victims of the quake which hit Turkey Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Aydin said that Turkey will soon form teams to select
settlement areas which are expected to be primarily set up in the
most quake-stricken provinces of Sakarya, Kocaeli and Yalova.
</P>
<P>
He said that the damage assestment work had already begun in
the less affected provinces of Eskisehir and Bolu and would begin
in Istanbul on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Similar work will start in the most devastated province of
Kocaeli and Sakarya once the rescue operations end, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
He added that prefabricated cities will be established in
temporary settlement places and the citizens will be able to pass
the winter in those places.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel has said that over 100,000
houses have been destroyed by the monster quake which has killed
at least 12,000 people in western Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Sakarya Governorship Crisis Administration Center said that
a total of 8,700 buildings collapsed in Adapazari (Sakarya)
province, over 11,000 buildings were seriously damaged and nearly
4,800 buildings were mildly or slightly damaged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
