<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Urges External Effort to Advance Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat on Sunday underlined the need for external effort to push
forward the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak in Alexandria, Arafat indicated he would asked
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to intervene
to break the deadlock in talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The situation needs an external effort to be exerted to push
the negotiations forward in a bid to implement what has been
agreed upon between the Palestinians and Israel, said Arafat, who
arrived in the Mediterranean port city of Alexandria earlier
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Albright is expected to visit the Mideast region in early
September after putting off an earlier visit due to Israel's
opposition to any third parties influencing the talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat expressed readiness to continue negotiations with Israel
to reach solutions satisfactory to the Palestinian people despite
frustration over Israel's delay of implementing the Wye peace
accord signed last October.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian and Israeli negotiators have been trying for days
to reach agreement on a timetable for completing all obligations
under the Wye agreement. The main points still to be resolved
remain the timetable for further Israeli troop withdrawal from the
West Bank and the release of Palestinians from Israeli prisons.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, a frequent visitor to Egypt, keeps close contacts with
Mubarak, who, as the president of the first Arab country to sign a
peace treaty with Israel, plays an active role in mediating the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with Mubarak, Arafat flew to Cairo for
a meeting later in the day with Nayef Hawatmeh, leader of the
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine (DFLP), as part
of the effort to reach a Palestinian national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first meeting between Arafat and Hawatmeh
since the 1993 signing of the Oslo accord, the main basis of the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
DFLP, based in the Syrian capital of Damascus, is opposed to
the Oslo accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
