<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Needs Local, Foreign Talents to Be World-Class: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong Sunday said that a competitive Singapore needs the help
from both local and foreign talents to become a world-class city.
</P>
<P>
To compete against the best in the world, Singapore has to
nurture its own talent and also bring in world-class companies and
the best people from outside, Goh said this in a speech delivered
at the National Day Rally here.
</P>
<P>
"Three million Singaporeans will not have enough talent to run
a first-world economy," said Goh. "we have to actively attract
able, creative and dynamic people from elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
By combining the strengths of both local and foreign talents,
Singapore can bring about faster growth and development and a
higher standard of living for all Singaporeans, he said.
</P>
<P>
Also, the talented Singaporeans will be very outward-looking
and more mobile as they will be able to choose where they want to
work and live, he said.
</P>
<P>
But if these people choose to work or stay away from Singapore
for long periods of time, Goh warned, the other Singaporeans and
the country will lose the help from them.
</P>
<P>
"This is an inevitable trend," he said. "we have to address,
rather than avoid, the issue."
</P>
<P>
By making itself a world-class home and a cosmopolitan city
with supplementary foreign talents, Singapore will be able to
secure more high-value investments to create good jobs, Goh said.
</P>
<P>
"All these will help to ensure that talented Singaporeans will
remain here to do their part for society and country," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
