<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Calls for Battle Against Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A greater effort needs to be
made in the battle against pollution, Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao said
today at a national conference on pollution prevention and control
in China's major river basins.
</P>
<P>
Wen said that although a great deal has been achieved in
curbing pollution in recent years and the water quality in some
major basins like Taihu Lake, the Huaihe River and Dianchi Lake
has improved, people still need to understand more about
environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
There are three problems to deal with: air pollution, water
pollution, and pollution caused by urban garbage, Wen said,
emphasizing that great importance must be placed on pollution
prevention and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
According to him, China's pollution problem can not be solved
in a short period of time, and a long-term program is needed to
tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
Wen asked government departments to make an effort to prevent
and curb pollution, to collect funds for environmental protection,
and to develop an environmental protection industry.
</P>
<P>
The conference was presided over by Xie Zhenghua, director of
the State Environmental Protection Administration. Its purpose was
to discuss water pollution prevention in major basins like Taihu
Lake and the Haihe and Liaohe rivers and to draw up a national
pollution control campaign.  
</P>
</TEXT>
