<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thorpe Sets WR at Pan Pacific Swimming Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, august 22 (Xinhua) -- Australian Ian Thorpe smashed
the 400 meters freestyle world record at the Pan Pacific swimming
championships in Sydney on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe completed the day by anchoring the Australian relay team
to victory over the United States.
</P>
<P>
Splashing in the very same pool for next year's Olympic Games,
Thorpe sliced almost two seconds off the previous 400m world mark.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe clocked three minutes 41.83 seconds to beat the previous
mark of 3:43.80, set by fellow Australian Kieren Perkins at the
1994 world championships in Rome.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe later helped the Australian 4x100m freestyle team down a
U.S. four for the first time. His final leg of 48.55sec helped
the Australian team win gold in 3:16.08 -- less than a second
outside the world record. And that brought about the first ever U.
S. defeat in the event at any major swimming meet.
</P>
<P>
The Americans came back to win the women's 4x100m freestyle
relay with Jenny Thompson anchoring the team to victory, and the
women's 25km open water race through the efforts by Briley Bergen,
who completed the race in five hours 16 minutes five seconds.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Joanne Malar took the women's 400m individual medley
in 4:40.23 while Australia's Mark Saliba won the men's 25km open
water event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
