<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lamas Attend China's National Games for Ethnic Solidarity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- We came here not only for the
medals, but also for the ethnic solidarity, the Lamas of Beijing-
based Yonghe Palace said after their competitions at the on-going
Chinese national ethnic games here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The three lamas, which represented Beijing to compete in the
top-whipping event, showed little sign of frustration although
they failed to make the last eight.
</P>
<P>
"We came here mainly for the sake of ethnic solidarity.
Whether win or loss doesn't matter much to us," said Kang Yujie,
the housekeeper of the Yonghe Palace.
</P>
<P>
His words were underlined as the three applauded sincerely to
congratulate on the victory of their opponents.
</P>
<P>
The lamas said they had long been inspired by the inscription
of Qian Long Emperor of the Qing Dynasty placed inside their
Beijing temple which read "The 56 nationalities in China are a
whole family."
</P>
<P>
"We have kept our faith to what he had said," said Kang. "We
have felt strongly the atmosphere of ethnic solidarity here and we
will cherish forever such friendship among us."
</P>
<P>
The failure in the competition, however, did not wear away
their interest in sports as they reeled off their daily sports
activities.
</P>
<P>
Kang, a sports fan himself, said that although they were
occupied with the routine Buddhist services, they have tried to
spare time for sports activities.
</P>
<P>
"Almost half of the lamas in Yonghe Palace are under 35, so
sports have been our major leisure activities," Kang said.
</P>
<P>
"We have managed to find some room from the parking lot in the
palace for basketball. We also built a badminton court to
entertain ourselves."
</P>
<P>
Kang has been a major factor in the sports enthusiasm in the
lamasery as he has so many business to handle every day.
</P>
<P>
"He often gets up at five every morning for Buddhist services.
And he also has to care about the daily management and reception,
but he has managed to find time to organize sports activities for
us," said another lama Bao Quangui.
</P>
<P>
"Under his push, we have sports games almost every week," Bao
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
