<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Encouraging China's Scientific Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- As the century ends, the Chinese
government is making its biggest ever attempt to encourage
scientific and technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to rank among world scientific giants in the
21st century and the Central Committee of the Communist Party and
State Council have decided to hold a National Technological
Innovation Conference later this month.
</P>
<P>
Some observers say that it will be important for building a
national innovation system and for high-tech ventures. The
government has already adopted measures to help build a national
innovation system and high-tech ventures in the past few months
and announced earlier this year that it will allocate 5 billion
yuan (600 million U.S. dollars) for the system. It will also
provide 600 million yuan for outstanding Chinese scientists
overseas to participate in the system research programs.
</P>
<P>
The government has established the State Supreme Science and
Technology Award that provides winners with 5 million yuan to
encourage scientists to work for major breakthroughs in research.
</P>
<P>
Early in 1995, President Jiang Zemin said that "innovation is
the soul of advancement in a nation and is the dynamic power for
building a prosperous and powerful country."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Wine Consumption Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese drink a third of a liter
of wine on average, which accounts for five percent of the world's
wine consumption per capita, according to the latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
It is still less than 0.5 percent of that in Western Europe,
according to the China Food Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
China's wine output in 1998 was 350,000 tons, which can meet
only 8.4 percent of the world's total demand. It is only five
percent of France's wine output.
</P>
<P>
China established more than 100 new wineries in 1997, with last
year's wine production increasing 52 percent from 1995. The
country also imported about 50,000 tons of wine last year.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Li Hua, a professor at Northwestern Agricultural University,
said that wine has been popular among Chinese since about 1995 and
has considerable opportunities at the Chinese market. Dry red wine
has been gaining much more in popularity than white in recent
years, mainly because of advertising and the romantic appeal,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
A greater effort is still needed to get Chinese to try the
taste of both red and white wine.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
