<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat-Mubarak Talks Positive: Palestinian Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
held "a positive and good" meeting with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak on Sunday, a senior Palestinian official said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Egypt's Mediterranean port city of Alexandria
earlier the day and briefed Mubarak on the Palestinian-Israeli
talks on reaching a timetable for the last two of the three-phased
Israeli troop withdrawals from the West Bank under the Wye peace
accord signed last October, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival at the Cairo International Airport following the
Palestinian-Egyptian summit, Palestinian Minister of Planning and
International Cooperation Nabil Shaath said the talks between the
two leaders underlined the key role Egypt plays in promoting the
Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
Shaath said the Egyptian president has exerted his utmost to
help the Palestinians and Israel work out the timetable for the
implementation of the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed to continue daily contacts in an
effort to keep Mubarak posted on the developments of the
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian and Israeli negotiators have been trying for days
to reach agreement on a timetable for completing all obligations
under the Wye agreement, including the opening of a safe passage
for the Palestinians between the West Bank and the Gaza Strip and
the opening of a Gaza seaport.
</P>
<P>
The main points still to be resolved remain the timetable for
completing further Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank and
the release of Palestinians from Israeli prisons.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the planned meeting between Arafat and Nayef
Hawatmeh, secretary general of the Democratic Front for the
Liberation of Palestine (DFLP), Shaath said the meeting is "very
important" and will bolster the efforts for Palestinian national
dialog.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is scheduled to lead later Sunday a delegation of his
Fatah movement to the meeting with the DFLP delegation to seek
reconciliation between the two rival groups within the Palestine
Liberation Organization (PLO).
</P>
<P>
The upcoming meeting will be the first between Arafat and
Hawatmeh since the 1993 signing of the Oslo accord, the main basis
of the Palestinian-Israeli talks. It is part of Arafat's effort to
reach national reconciliation and a united Palestinian position on
the final status talks with Israel on the thorny and significant
issues, including Jerusalem and the Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier step on August 1, Arafat met with a delegation of
the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine (PFLP), another
radical group in the PLO. The two sides agreed to continue dialog
and called on other groups to join the process.
</P>
<P>
Fatah is the major force to support the Palestinian-Israeli
peace talks. DFLP and PFLP, both based in the Syrian capital of
Damascus, are opposed to the Oslo accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
