<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Encouraging China's Scientific Development (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics show 2.8 million people are engaged in scientific
and technological research and there are over 21,600 research and
development institutes in China.
</P>
<P>
The government has also allocated a large amount of funds for
major scientific research projects. The second-phase of the
national synchrotron lab, an earth crest monitoring system, a
large fiber spectroscopy telescope, and the HT-7U Tok Mark fusion
device have been going on since 1996. They are expected to provide
support for major research programs.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yongxiang, the president of the Chinese Academy of Sciences,
says that the world is entering an era of knowledge-backed
economies and, in some developed countries, new developments
contribute 60 to 80 percent of economic growth, but China has a
lot to do in improving its innovative ability and applying high-
tech discoveries.
</P>
<P>
He says China could achieve sustainable development in the 21st
century if it adopts a rational development strategy and faces the
reality of challenges in scientific and technological development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
