<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Assist Nigeria on Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has listed
environmental projects and promised to support this projects with
community-based approaches and targets the reversal of
environmental degradation and poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Trever Byer, Resident Representative of the Bank to Nigeria,
stressed the need for the bank to consolidate its alliance with
organizations like the Worldwide Fund for Nature (WWN) and the
Nigerian Conservation Foundation (NCF), the Guardian, a leading
newspaper in the country reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We have to look for areas where we can move forward," he said
noting that "it is not how much that counts but the level of
expertise and commitment demonstrated by people in doing things."
</P>
<P>
The organization has suspended all forms of new assistance to
Nigeria since 1993 due to what the bank called "poor results and
unfavorable political environment."
</P>
<P>
"Since 1993, our portfolio of activities has worn down
considerably", said Byer, adding that since then the Bank's
projects have reduced from 58 to 8. By March next year, all its
current projects would have been wound up.
</P>
<P>
The bank official agreed that Nigeria is bedeviled by many
environmental problems ranging from desert encroachment in the
North and pollution problems in the south to massive soil erosion
in the East.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
