<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gemstones Smuggled out of Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Most of quality gemstones
produced in Tanzania are not available in the country but are
found in the neighboring country Kenya, a local newspaper said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey by the Sunday Observer, Kenyan capital
Nairobi is fast becoming the unofficial regional marketing nerve
center for Tanzania's gemstones.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that most of Tanzania's gemstones find their way
outside the country's border through Nairobi, east Africa's
biggest city, where they are said to fetch a much higher price
than elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's gemstones find their way to Nairobi through porous
border between the two countries, it said.
</P>
<P>
A number of mineral and gemstone dealers in Dar es Salaam last
week told the paper that people can hardly find quality gemstones
in the formerly self-created marketing towns in Tanzania. By
contrast Nairobi abounds in all sorts of quality gemstones from
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is believed to be second only to the Democratic
Republic of Congo as the most important source of precious stones
in the southern African region.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that things began going wrong as long ago
as the early 1980s, particularly as tanzanite gained in
importance. Tanzanite is a precious blue stone produced only in
Tanzania, specifically in the volcanic soils to the southwest of
Mount Kilimanjaro. Strangely, Kenya now stands as the world's
largest exporter of this unique product.
</P>
<P>
Apart from tanzanite, Tanzanian gemstones most commonly found
on sale in Nairobi include green tourmaline, sapphire, garnet,
diamonds, rubies and emeralds.
</P>
<P>
Local mine dealers and brokers observed that gemstones and
minerals were also smuggled out of the country to Zambia, Malawi
and South Africa because of loose border checks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian House Speaker Counter-attacks President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) (C Nigerian Speaker of the House of
Representatives, Alhaji Ghali Na'aba Saturday accused President
Olusegun Obasanjo of high-handedness on state matters, saying that
most of his policy initiatives and actions are capable of
derailing democracy.
</P>
<P>
Na'aba made the counter-attack when addressing the secretariat
of the Nigeria Union of Journalists (NUJ) in the country's
Northern state Kaduna, the Guardian, a leading Nigerian
newspapers reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said that, "I want to say that the executive arm of
government in Nigeria has been high-handed towards its legislative
and judicial counterparts and this is undermining democracy and I
want to assure you all that we shall resist it and we shall
continue to resist it."
</P>
<P>
The House had earlier demanded an apology from Obasanjo for his
 criticism on some legislators
</P>
<P>
But the president's spokesman, Doyin Okupe, said at the weekend
that Obasanjo does not intend to offer an apology. He said the
president's criticism on the top legislators lackluster was based
on an honest assessment of the lawmakers' showing.
</P>
<P>
Members of the National Assembly had frowned at the remarks
made by the president that the Assembly had been doing little or
nothing in its almost two months of inauguration.
</P>
<P>
Okupe said, "It is ridiculous to ask the president to apologize
for a statement he made as a citizen of this country, as a
president of this country.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a military regime. This is democracy. The
president combines two rights as the president. The president
says I have sent so much to the place and not much has happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
