<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New China At Fifty (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- In the eyes of the Chinese, this
year is one of big events and jubilation.
</P>
<P>
The 50th anniversary of the People's Republic is the most
important. On October 1, there will be a grand ceremony in the
capital, Beijing, and parties all across the country for the
occasion. The 50 years of achievements are the pride of every
Chinese, who have every reason to express their enormous joy.
Under the leadership of the Communist Party, the Chinese spent
years fighting for the socialist China that was established on
October 1, 1949. For the past half century, although there have
been detours, the government has devoted itself to living up to
its goal of working for the interest of the people.
</P>
<P>
Now the country's overall strength has increased and all 56
ethnic groups are getting along well with each other and have
peaceful and happy lives and the nation's international status has
grown considerably.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Jun, a TV producer from southwest China's Sichuan Province,
says that in the more than 100 years before 1949, China struggled
much of the time against foreign invasions or in wars between
warlords and every year several million people died from conflicts
and calamities.
</P>
<P>
A stable and secure government would have been a luxury in
those dark years, he says, but Chinese governments before the
founding of the People's Republic failed to produce the yearned-
for political stability. Only in 1949 was China, led by the
Communist Party, able to bring about what the Chinese had longed
for and to establish national pride.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Hu An'gang, of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, says that
since the founding of the New China, a powerful central government
has been established, bringing about the successful
industrialization and modernization and social stability and
economic prosperity have helped increase people's confidence in
the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Play Leading Role in World Postal Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- China will play a leading role
in the world's postal services in the next five years because of
its extensive postal network, a senior official of the Universal
Postal Union (UPU) said here today.
</P>
<P>
As the presiding nation of the UPU Administrative Council in
the five years to come, China will serve as an example for the 170
developing countries of the 189 member countries in upgrading
postal services, said Thomas Leavey, director-general of the UPU's
International Bureau.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held today on the eve of the 22nd
Universal Postal Congress (UPC), which opens in Beijing on Monday,
he said that China is an important member of the international
community and a permanent member of the UN Security Council while
it has a prominent role in the UPU.
</P>
<P>
Leavey said he has never seen such good preparations and
facilities for a UPC, adding that at the International
Telecommunications Union congress last year in the United States
he did not see facilities as good as what he saw in Beijing in the
past two days.
</P>
<P>
Liu Pingyuan, secretary-general of the UPC organizing committee,
said that all preparatory work for the congress is completed and 2,
319 delegates are expected, including 68 at ministerial level and
260 at vice-ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
This will be the most heavily attended highest level congress
of the UPU in its 125-year history, Liu added.
</P>
<P>
The congress will be held from August 23 to September 15.
Chinese President Jiang Zemin will preside over an opening
ceremony on Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
