<HEADLINE> Myanmar Gets Less Customs Duties Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar gained a total of 246
million U.S. dollars in customs duties in the first four months of
this year, 321 million dollars less than that received in the same
period of last year which was 567 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest economic indicators published by the
country's Central Statistical Organization, of the total customs
duties obtained in the four-month period, import duties were 221
million dollars, while that in the corresponding period of last
year amounted to 353 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The indicators also show that the country's customs duties
income dropped from 1.274 billion dollars in 1997 to 1.135 billion
dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Myanmar has made some adjustments in the rate
of customs duties in an effort to boost the development of
agriculture. The country exempted import duties on agricultural
implements including machinery, pesticide and fertilizer while
raising import duties on luxury goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
