<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obasanjo to Have Public Email Address </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigerians are to get directly in
touch with President Olusegun Obasanjo through an E-mail messaging
system expected to come into effect before the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
Steve Itugbu, special assistant to the president on press
matters, said that the introduction of the system would offer the
opportunity to discuss government policies and actions with the
president, The Post Express reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The special assistant noted that the move was part of the
efforts of the Obasanjo administration to encourage transparency
and discourage rumor mongering with regards to government policies
and actions.
</P>
<P>
The president's address is "President
Obasanjo@nigeria.gov.org.". The official added that a reply
acknowledging the receipt of the mail will be relayed instantly.
</P>
<P>
After investigation if necessary, the president will personally
send a reply to the mailer addressing the issues, and any
information will be kept secret as the email would be assessed
only by the president and his personal assistant, Itugbu said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the novel approach to government/citizen
relationship would eliminate the tedious process Nigerians go
through to see the president often times without success as their
efforts are thwarted by both security operatives and an army of
personal aides.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the email system, he disclosed, there are also
efforts in the pipeline for a presidency website that would be
used by any information seeking Nigerian or non-Nigerian
interested in the activities of the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Says Government Ready to Help Overseas Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government Sunday
assured several million Overseas Filipino Workers (OFWs) that it
remains committed to help them have gainful jobs in the
Philippines once they return for good.
</P>
<P>
The Overseas Workers Welfare Administration (OWWA) has lined up
seminars and other programs that would help returning OFWs start
their own livelihood programs, President Joseph Estrada said in a
statement issued here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"I encourage you to go to OWWA. It has a livelihood division
that has projects for OFWs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said that the OWWA and its partners also give seminars
and loan assistance packages to returning OFWs who wish to start
their own businesses in the country.
</P>
<P>
The government considers OFWs as modern-day heroes because of
the vital role they play in their host countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the government, at least 4 million OFWs are
working in 182 countries and regions in the world and remit 5
billion to 6 billion dollars a year to their country.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the government has lined up several benefit
programs and packages for them and their families, such as loan
assistance, entrepreneurial opportunities, housing programs and
medical care packages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
