<HEADLINE> Pak Facilitating Afghan Factions to End Conflict: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz said Sunday Pakistan is only trying to facilitate the
Afghan warring factions to put an end to the war and find a way
for restoring peace in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
"We are not mediating rather only trying to facilitate the two
sides (the Taliban and the opposition alliance) to hold talks,"
the Associated Press of Pakistan quoted Aziz as saying during an
interview with BBC.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that the anti-Taliban alliance itself had asked
Islamabad to help end the long-running fighting.
</P>
<P>
"We had received a message from Professor (Burhanuddin) Rabbani
(former Afghan president) that the war has prolonged and we should
assist them in this regard. Obviously we have since long been
trying to put an end to the war and find a way for restoration of
peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Pakistani government earlier this week sent a
delegation to Dushanbe, capital of Tajikistan, for talks with the
anti-Taliban alliance.
</P>
<P>
"Now our delegation has been sent to Kandahar to inform the
Taliban of the proposals and views of the opposition," he added.
</P>
