<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Artifacts Back to Egypt from Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Sunday took back home 28
pieces of ancient antiquities handed over by Jordan, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Gaballah Ali Gaballah, head of the Egyptian Supreme Council for
Antiquities, who represented Egypt in the handover ceremony of the
antiquities in Jordan on Wednesday, returned to Cairo with the
precious pieces earlier on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon arrival at Cairo International
Airport, Gaballah praised the Jordanian government's assistance in
the return of 28 artifacts to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"The interference of the Jordanian prime minister and the
tourism minister has helped in the retrieval of the Egyptian
artifacts smuggled (into the kingdom)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan on Wednesday handed over to Egypt the 28 pieces of
ancient anticrafts stolen from various Egyptian archaeological
sites, smuggled into the kingdom but intercepted in Jordan's Red
Sea port of Aqaba last April.
</P>
<P>
Gaballah said the antiquities include six turquoise and brown
magic charms believed to have fended off illness and date back to
650 B.C. or the Late Period, and 21 bluish Pharaonic statues, each
10 centimeters high, called the Shawabti, or the answer, which
used to be buried with the dead to serve them in the other world.
</P>
<P>
He said the most significant of all was a 30-kilogram head of
the statue of Serapis, an ancient god worshiped by the people of
Alexandria in the Ptolemaic age that dates back to the first
century A.D. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
