<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Tries to Attract More Foreign Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
taking measures to entice millions of Filipino expatriates or
foreigners with Filipino roots to visit the Philippines and
convince their neighbors or fellow workers to do the same.
</P>
<P>
In a report released here Sunday, Tourism Secretary Gemma Cruz
Araneta said that her department aims to tap overseas Filipinos
with its recent launching of "the Tourism Frontliners" and "the
Discover Your Roots" projects.
</P>
<P>
To help market the country as a premier tourist destination in
the region, Araneta said her department would revive the Overseas
Philippine Tourism Councils and at the same time establish
Philippine overseas youth councils in key cities in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The Tourism Frontliners program aims to tap 6.97 million
overseas Filipinos as frontliners for tourism marketing and
promotions in their places of work and their communities in return
for a package of incentives, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Discover Your Roots program, the official said, is designed
to woo third-and fourth-generation Filipino-Americans living in
the United States to visit their ancestral homeland and rediscover
their cultural roots.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show there are 2,940,082 Filipinos working
abroad; another 2,153,967 are residing permanently in different
countries; and 1.88 million more are undocumented ones.
</P>
<P>
A Philippine delegation led by Araneta launched these projects
earlier this month during a two-week sales mission in the United
States, which is home to 1.69 million Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
The United States remains as the country's main tourist market,
accounting for 468,808 tourists last year, 65,821 of them
Filipino-Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
