<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, August 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- At least three people were killed and eight others
were injured in a new riot in Ambon, capital of Indonesia's Maluku
province, on Saturday afternoon, the Antara News Agency reported
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The rioters attacked a shophouse complex and torched 10 of the
complex's units with self-made incendiary bombs and molotov
cocktails. (Indonesia-Riot)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- A group of armed men shot dead five more
villagers in northern Colombia on Saturday, bringing the total
murdered in the week to at least 20, a police source said. (
Colombia-Paramilitary-Killings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada's Supreme Court Chief Justice Antonio Lamer on
Saturday announced his resignation on January 7 of next year.
</P>
<P>
Lamer said the position is no longer appealing to him years
after he was first appointed chief justice in 1989, according to
Canadian media. (Canada-Justice-Resignation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABUJA -- The Council of Ministers of the Economic Community of
the West Africa States (ECOWAS) decided Friday night in Abuja to
impose sanctions against members owing the organization some 37.2
million U.S. dollars in contribution arrears. (ECOWAS-Finance)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- Uganda has accused Burundi for helping Rwandan
troops in the Kisangani battle in which about 30 Ugandan soldiers
died.
</P>
<P>
The accusation was made by Kahinda Otafiire, President Yoweri
Museveni's adviser on the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC),
the New Vision paper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said Burundi has at least 4,000 troops in Kisangani backing
Rwandan Patriotic Army (RPA) against Ugandan soldiers and the
Burundi troops had got involved in Kisangani clashes a week ago.
(Uganda-Burundi-Ties) 
</P>
</TEXT>
