<HEADLINE> Uganda Army Rejects Imported Rotten Food from S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Uganda People's Defense Forces
(UPDF) has rejected tinned food rations and biscuits recently
imported from South Africa after chemists declared them unfit for
human consumption.
</P>
<P>
The decision follows the findings of top chemists who inspected
the food in Jinja and Magamaga Ordinance Depot where the
consignment was kept.
</P>
<P>
The rations, supplied by Kramer Trade and Technology and meant
for UPDF soldiers in war zones, are worth two billion shillings
(1.5 million U.S. dollars), the New Vision paper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The food includes chicken, beans and biscuits.
</P>
<P>
The UPDF's Chief of Personnel and Administration Steven Ksahaka
was quoted as saying Saturday that the army had rejected the bad
dry ration and would not pay for it.
</P>
<P>
The chemists' report describing the food as something the army
should not accept was already presented to the South Africans at a
meeting with UPDF and defense ministry officials, according to the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
