<HEADLINE> 4 More Earthquake Victims Rescued in Turkey After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Weak but alive, a 95-year-old
woman was pulled out of the ruins of a vacation home by a Turkish
rescue team in the earthquake-hit township of Cinarcik Saturday,
the Turkish Daily News reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A few hours earlier, nearby, a 10-year-old Israeli girl who
had been buried under the rubble of her family's summer house
since Tuesday had been rescued by Israeli rescue teams, said the
English-language newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Defying ever waning hopes, four quake victims were rescued
alive on the day, four days after after Tuesday's massive
earthquake in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In Golcuk, two sisters identified as Ilknur Cengiz, 19, and
Oznur Cengiz, 10, were pulled out by French and Turkish
crews. They had been trapped under the rubble for 116 hours. The
teams were now trying to save a woman who lived on the floor below
the sisters.
</P>
<P>
Experts say people trapped in such situations usually can
survive only 72 hours because of dehydration. The sweltering heat
of the week made conditions even worse, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
The distressing truth, however, is that there are tens of
thousands of people still missing and that with every victims
pulled out of debris alive, rescuers are recovering hundreds of
corpses as official death toll rose to 12,040 Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The massive quake, with a magnitude of 7.4 degrees on the
Richter scale, rocked heavily-populated northwest Turkish
provinces near the Marmara Sea at 3:02 a.m. (0002 GMT) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Since then, there have been 1,300 aftershocks in the region,
dozens of which registered at four degrees or above.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates have put direct economic loss of the
quake at between 20 and 40 billion U.S. dollars, though no
concrete figures could be concluded as rescue works were still
going on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
