<HEADLINE> Kenya Ready for National Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The preparation for the Kenya's
1999 national census falling on August 24 night are complete with
the establishment of a census surveillance and complaints bureau
to monitor activities on the ground, Kenyan Vice-President George
Saitoti has said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president Saturday made the remarks at a press
briefing in the capital Nairobi, saying more than 100,000
personnel had bee mobilized, including 13,000 supervisors and
82,000 enumerators.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Nation quoted Saitoti as saying cartographic mapping
of the country had been completed, and maps, questionnaires and
other requisite materials had already been distributed to various
districts.
</P>
<P>
According to the vice-president, the government would spend
about 1.8 billion shilling (some 25 million U.s. dollars) on the
project.
</P>
<P>
The government will meet 75 percent of the total cost while
development partners have given 305 million shillings (some 4.23
million dollars) for the purpose, Saitoti said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that any census official found misappropriating
census funds will be dealt with harshly.
</P>
<P>
Nairobi Provincial Commissioner Cyrus Maina, who is the
chairman of the National Census Steering Committee, urged Kenyans
to cooperate with the census officials to ensure accurate and
efficient count.
</P>
<P>
He said security plans were complete and police officers will
start conducting night patrol to detect ad arrest criminals.
</P>
<P>
The week-long national census will end on August 31 and the
preliminary results of the census will be made public after six
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
