<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Gets Tough On Debtor Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Ministers of the
Economic Community of the West Africa States (ECOWAS) decided
Friday night in Abuja to impose sanctions against members owing
the organization some 37.2 million US dollars in contribution
arrears.
</P>
<P>
The decision, adopted at its three-day 44th session, is in
response to the financial problem hindering the integration of
the 24-year-old body, reported the Pan-African New Agency (PANA).
</P>
<P>
The ministers called for the invocation of article 77 which
among others,
</P>
<P>
stipulates that debtor nations be denied voting rights, while
their nationals are to be excluded from appointments into
statutory and professional positions of ECOWAS. grouping 16 west
African states
</P>
<P>
Such members would also lose loans and other financial
assistance and the right to air their views on community matters.
</P>
<P>
The council also set up a six-member ad-hoc committee on the
restructuring of the ECOWAS secretariat to make the organization
more effective.
</P>
<P>
The committee was given two months to prepare proposals ahead
of the October or November summit.
</P>
<P>
Some members have suggested a new structure with four deputy
executive secretaries as against the current three and the
scrapping of the position of financial controller to be replaced
by the internal auditor.
</P>
<P>
The present quota arrangement whereby posts are zoned to
countries has equally been criticized with a suggestion for an
equitable formula taking into account the geographical spread and
financial contributions of members.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS fund is also to be restructured to create what the
ministers called a holding company to be known as ECOWAS Bank for
Investment and Development which would have two subsidiaries - a
regional investment bank and development fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
