<HEADLINE> Philippines Works out Plan to Fight Forest Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines government Sunday
ordered local government units to beef up their forest
fire-fighting capabilities amid the resurgence of forest fires in
neighboring Malaysia and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Sunday, Antonio Cerilles, secretary
of the Department of Environment and Natural Resources, said that
the department's fire-fighting teams have been on 24-hour alert
and are constantly monitoring the possible occurrence of forest
fires nationwide.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government issued the order "following the
recurrence of forest fires in Southeast Asian countries like
Indonesia and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Cerilles said he has directed the department's regional
directors to mobilize all 6,000 foresters and forest rangers
nationwide to man all existing fire lookout stations and be in
close touch with local governments for forest-fire control.
</P>
<P>
Local officials should "remain on alert for possible forest
fires in their areas in view of the recurrence of the problem in
Southeast Asian countries despite the wet season," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Sumatra and Kalimantan were again hit by
debilitating smog caused by forest fires recently. Authorities
said that the fires were caused by large plantations which burned
wooded land to clear it for planting.
</P>
<P>
As part of a long-term plan to allow government to best deal
with this problem, Cerilles said the government would initially
"seek the help of the Japanese government in acquiring free
fire-fighting equipment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
