<HEADLINE> Uganda Accuses Burundi of Helping Rwandans in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has accused Burundi for
helping Rwandan troops the Kisangani battle in which about 30
Ugandan soldiers died.
</P>
<P>
The accusation was made by Kahinda Otafiire, President Yoweri
Museveni's adviser on the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC),
the New Vision paper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said Burundi has at least 4,000 troops in Kisangani backing
Rwandan Patriotic Army (RPA) against Ugandan soldiers and the
Burundi troops had participated in Kisangani clashes a week ago.
</P>
<P>
However, there has not been any response from Rwanda and
Burundi to this accusation.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Rwandan Vice President and Minister of
Defense Paul Kagame arrives in Kampala Sunday to hold talks with
Museveni on the DRC issue. DRC rebel leader Wamba dia Wamba is
also here on his way to Lusaka to sign the ceasefire agreement,
the report added.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day clashes between Ugandan and Rwandan troops
in Kisangani, both sides sustained heavy losses. The fighting
prompted an urgent meeting of Museveni and Kagame in western
Uganda on Monday and Tuesday and it came up with a ceasefire
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda, former friendly allies, turned against each
other after the DRC rebel group the Congolese Rally for Democracy
split into two opposing factions in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
This friction between two friends has widely been regarded as
further complicating the fragile peace process of the third
largest African country.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, Both Museveni and Rwandan President
Pasteur Bizimungu were invited to the 19th summit of the Southern
African Development Community to discuss the issue. 
</P>
