<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Vietnam Intensifies Anti-Drug Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has gotten good results in
anti-drug drive, but the situation of the anti-drug fight in the
country is still complicated.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai has appealed for
intensifying anti-drug drive and achieving more success in the
fight against drug-related crimes and drug abuse to ensure
national stability and sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government launched an anti-drug drive on
November 30, 1998 and has worked out an anti-drug action program
for the 1998-2000 period, focusing on raising public awareness of
the harms of drug abuse and mobilizing everybody, every family and
the whole society to participate in the drive of preventing and
fighting drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
The National Drug Control Committee held a conference in Hanoi
on Saturday (August 21) to review drug control efforts in the
national anti-drug drive.
</P>
<P>
According to Vietnam's Minister of Public Security and Vice
Chairman of the National Drug Control Committee Le Minh Huong,
from November 30 last year to August 15 this year, Vietnam's
special task forces detected almost 8,200 drug-related crimes,
arresting 16,820 offenders and seizing more than 46 kg of heroin,
252.6 kg of opium and 319 kg of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
People's courts at all levels in the country tried 3,310 drug
cases with 4,952 defendants in the period from December 1998 to
May this year, sentencing 35 to death.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to eradicate the growing of opium poppy have also
yielded good results. From 12,000 hectares of opium poppy in 1993,
the country now has only nine hectares left scatteredly in
northern mountainous provinces.
</P>
<P>
By May this year, the country had 97,000 drug addicts under
monitoring and 8,000 drug-addicted prisoners. Over the past nine
months, almost 9,000 addicts have been treated at detoxification
centers under the Ministry of Labor, War Invalids and Social
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Almost 3,340 others were detoxified at communal centers or at
home, and 1,200 rehabilitated people were given occupational
training and jobs.
</P>
<P>
Drug abuse among young people has also been reduced thanks to
intensified education and prevention measures undertaken by the
Ministry of Education and Training in coordination with relevant
agencies.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government also attaches importance to the
international cooperation in controlling cross-border drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Authorities of provinces along both sides of the Vietnam-Laos
border line had met to discuss cooperation in this field. Vietnam
has participated in six sub-regional drug control projects and
joined a system of ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
to exchange information on criminals, including drug-related
criminals. It has also coordinated with Interpol (International
Police Organization) and other countries to detect more than 30
international drug-related crimes in the reviewed period. The
United Nations and a number of non-governmental organizations have
provided financial support to Vietnam's four national drug control
projects.
</P>
<P>
However, Le Minh Huong noted that the situation remains
worrisome with failures in stopping the flow of drug across the
border, the increasing complication in drug-related crimes and
unstable results in eradicating the growing of opium poppy.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai, at the conference held
by the National Drug Control Committee, also pointed out the wide
spread of drug-related crimes, saying that drug abuse is causing
concern to every family and the whole society. It is a threat to
the country's sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Khai called on Vietnam's relevant agencies and the entire
people to raise their sense of responsibility and create more
positive changes in preventing and fighting drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's special task forces and relevant ministries plan to
intensify their efforts in education and prevention measures
against drug-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
The National Drug Control Committee of the country will ask the
government to allow the establishment of a "Drug Control Fund" and
an additional 10 billion Vietnamese dong (about 720 thousand U.S.
dollars) for the task in the remaining months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Committee also plans to work out and sign cooperation
agreements on drug control with the United States, China and other
ASEAN countries and boost its cooperation with the UN
International Drug Control Program (UNDCP) and Interpol. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
