<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 06:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Cuts Car Duties, Raises Petrol Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has decided to cut off
customs and taxes on cars by an average of 67 percent, but to
increase petrol prices to compensate for the losses of the state
treasury.
</P>
<P>
Duties on cars with engine capacities below 1,500 cubic
centimeters (cc) will be reduced to 60 percent from 105 percent,
1,500-2,000cc cars to 80 percent from 136 percent, according to
the a decision made after a cabinet meeting on Saturday,
</P>
<P>
Duties on 2,000-2,500cc and over 2,500cc cars will be reduced
to 100 and 120 percent respectively from 200 percent.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of duties on imported cars was expected to cause
some 37 million Jordanian dinars (51.8 million U.S. dollars) to
the state treasury, the semi-officials Jordan Times said.
</P>
<P>
The government decided to raise petrol prices to 400 fils (0.56
dollars) from 380 fils (0.53 dollars) to patch up for the losses
caused by the reduction of duties on cars.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 million dinars (28 million dollars) will be recouped by
increasing the gas prices plus registration and licensing fees,
and the remaining 17 million dinar (23.8 million dollars) will be
handled by the treasury itself, Prime Minister Abdul Raouf
Rawabdeh said.
</P>
<P>
The decision to reduce car duties was believed to be part
of the kingdom`s efforts to join the World Trade Organization,
which generally calls for the reduction of customs duties to
encourage free trade.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is unable to produce cars, and vehicles on the Jordanian
roads are mainly imported from Germany, Japan, South Korea, France
and other major world car producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
