<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 06:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pan-Arab Games Lower Flags to Mourn Saudi Prince </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Flags at the ninth Pan-Arab Games
in Amman will be flown half-mast for three days from Sunday to
mourn the death of Saudi Prince Faisal Ben Fahd, the eldest son
of Saudi King Fahd.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing Pan-Arab games would continue as scheduled at the
request of Saudi Arabia despite the passing away of Prince Faisal,
who died of a heart attack Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Faisal had been the de facto Saudi sports minister and also
head of the Arab Sports Federation of the 22-member Arab League.
</P>
<P>
However, competitions slated for Sunday would be postponed for
three hours and all matches will be preceded by a moment of
silence in memory of Faisal.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made late Saturday after an emergency meeting
of the Organizing Committee of the Pan-Arab Games.
</P>
<P>
"The Saudis have informed us that they do not wish to see the
Games suspended," said Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister Ayman
Majali after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Faisal visited Amman last Sunday to attend the opening ceremony
of the ninth Pan-Arab Games, the largest and last Arab sports
event of the century.
</P>
<P>
He died shortly after returning to Saudi Arabia from Amman.
</P>
<P>
"We have lost one of the pillars of Arab sports," said Sheikh
Issa Ben Rashid of Bahrain, deputy president of the Arab Sports
Federation after hearing the death of Faisal.
</P>
<P>
A record 4,600 athletes from 21 Arab countries took part in the
ninth Pan-Arab games in Jordan with Kuwait sending an official
delegation headed by a minister.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait boycotted the games to protest against the participation
of Iraqi athletes as the two countries are still hostile to each
other nine years after the Gulf war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
