<HEADLINE> Canadian Chief Justice Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Supreme Court Chief
Justice Antonio Lamer Saturday announced his resignation on
January 7 of next year.
</P>
<P>
Lamer said the position is no longer appealing to him years
after he was first appointed chief justice in 1989, according to
Canadian media.
</P>
<P>
"What was a very demanding, nevertheless challenging, period of
my professional life is gradually becoming a job," the 66-year-old
chief justice told a Canadian Bar Association meeting in Edmonton,
Alberta.
</P>
<P>
Lamer, the longest-serving member of Canada's highest court,
began his 10th year as chief justice in July. He was a well-known
criminal lawyer before he became a judge almost 40 years ago, the
media said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
