<HEADLINE> British Columbia Premier Quits amid Scandal Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Glen Clark, premier of Canada's
western province of British Columbia, resigned a day after he was
put under criminal investigation Friday.
</P>
<P>
CTV said Clark tendered his resignation earlier Saturday, but
maintained he had done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
"I'm completely confident I will be exonerated and cleared,"
Clark told reporters later, but adding "I've concluded it would be
wrong of me to continue."
</P>
<P>
Canadian Attorney General Ujjal Dosanjh announced Friday that
Clark "is under criminal investigation" because of possible
involvement in corruption.
</P>
<P>
Clark is alleged to have worked "vigorously" for a friend to
get a casino license. In return, he could receive 15 percent of
the profits from the casino owner, the television said. 
</P>
