<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Says Y2K Problem Is Far from Solved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese senior official said
that although China has taken many measures to solve the Y2K
problem, the situation is not satisfactory in some places.
</P>
<P>
Today's "China Daily" quoted Zhang Qi, an official with the
Ministry of Information Industry, as saying that the sectors of
finance, securities, aviation and telecommunications have finished
modifying their systems and have undergone nationwide tests,
however, there are still problems in power and petroleum
industries.
</P>
<P>
The paper did not give any detailed information, but noted that
China is also facing difficulty because there are no laws dealing
with the issue.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that there will be possible legal disputes that
might arise because of the Y2K problem, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
Officials and experts will go to the United States to study
what the US has done in the legal area to tackle the problem,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K crisis would break out before and after December 31,
1999, or January 1, 2000, because many older computers would mis-
treat 2000 as 1900 because of their program design. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
