<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former UK PM Sees Great Changes in China Over Past Decades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Former British prime minister
Edward Heath smiled as he looked back upon his "growing
understanding" of China over the years, telling the "three things"
he felt proud of as someone with a five-decade-long political
career behind.
</P>
<P>
He summed up his observation of China's changes over the
decades in the light of his exchanges with the People's Republic
of China, which will celebrate the 50th anniversary of its
founding on October 1.
</P>
<P>
As a one-time political heavy-weight in the world, the 83-year-
old Heath is one of the few foreign personalities who have had
close contacts with the three generations of the Chinese
leadership.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua, he recalled meetings with
Chinese leaders spanning the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
"All the leaders were remarkable in the way they discussed the
full range of issues, quick and sharp in thinking and talking,
each though with his own focus of interest," Heath said. "Chairman
Mao (Zedong) liked to talk about international affairs. Chairman
Deng (Xiaoping) tended to focus on domestic issues, mostly the
economy of China, and he could be so specific as to go into the
details of agriculture. And President Jiang (Zemin) seemed to be
interested in the organization of the country, or the perfection
of the institutions, political and economic, in addition to his
apparent attention to the world's issues."
</P>
<P>
He agreed that the different focuses, in a sense, reflected the
changes China had undergone over the decades.
</P>
<P>
The late 1970s, when Heath met twice with late Chairman Mao,
showed emerging signs of China's overall opening to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
The 1980s, when he had a number of audiences with Deng Xiaoping,
the chief architect of China's reform program, marked an era of
the fastest economic development in Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the 1990s, Heath has met with Jiang
Zemin and other top Chinese leaders on several occasions, whose
conversations indicate China's growing maturity toward overall
modernization, along with the enhancement of national strength,
international status, and increasing influence in the global
economic system.
</P>
<P>
Heath, who will shortly go on his 24th visit to China, said
that he "never failed to be surprised" in each of his previous 23
visits to China in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
"The nation has literally been transformed, just as the roads
and skyline of Beijing, and the newly-developed area in Shanghai,"
he said, referring to China as a country with the greatest changes
in the last decades of this century.
</P>
<P>
As he played a special part in the resolution of the Hong Kong
issue between Britain and China, the memory of that constituted a
sense of pride for Heath too. He first discussed the issue of Hong
Kong's stable transfer with veteran Chinese leaders during his
first visit to China in 1974.
</P>
<P>
He recalled his meeting in April, 1982 with Deng Xiaoping,
during which the late Chinese leader expounded for the first time
China's principles on resolving the Hong Kong issue, including the
resumption of exercise of sovereignty, establishment of a special
administrative region in Hong Kong which would be ruled by local
people while preserving Hong Kong's social system.
</P>
<P>
Having visited Hong Kong on two occasions since attending the
handover ceremony in 1997, Heath said the he was satisfied with
the social stability, economic development and smooth operation of
the political system in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has largely overcome the difficulties that arose with
the Asian crisis "due to the correct decisions made in Beijing as
well as in Hong Kong," he said, adding that the policy of "one
country two systems" has proved highly successful and produced the
best possible result for Hong Kong itself, for China, for Britain,
and for the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Hong Kong model could work elsewhere in the world
for settling problems left from history and the historic event
represented a major contribution to the development of world
politics in the 20th century, he said.
</P>
<P>
Heath believed that Macao's return at the end of this year
would undoubtedly be as smooth as Hong Kong's return and the
Taiwan issue would be resolved sooner or later with a similar
approach.
</P>
<P>
Another special episode in Heath's ties with China was the
establishment of Sino-British diplomatic relations at the
ambassadorial level in 1972 when he was the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of Sino-British relations, for example, generally
coincided with the development of China itself, said Heath.
</P>
<P>
Now, Heath noted, Sino-British relations face a new period of
expansion, for Britain and Europe as a whole increasingly
appreciate the importance of good ties with China.
</P>
<P>
So long as China would manage to sustain its economic growth
along the present path of success, the country will undoubtedly
grow stronger and more powerful, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
