<HEADLINE> Over 50 tons of Cocaine Go through C. America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- More than 50 tons of cocaine
out of the 850 tons moved by international drug traffickers go
through Central America every year, parliamentarians of the region
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At its fifth regional meeting held here Friday, the Central
American Interparliamentary Commission Against Corruption and Drug
Trafficking (CICONA) noted that Central America has become an
important "bridge" for international drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Among the 850 tons of cocaine trafficked each year, it said,
650 tons go to the United States and 150 tons to Europe.
</P>
<P>
Besides exchanging views on the drug-related problems in the
countries of the isthmus, the parliamentarians also proposed the
creation of antidrug regional police and the coordination of
relevant laws.
</P>
<P>
They revealed that the first regional summit against drug
trafficking will be held in Costa Rica next February to discuss
the creation of a Central American anti-drug police.
</P>
<P>
The legislators urged to study the eventual extradition of
nationals involved in drug trafficking, which is forbidden at
present by most of the constitutions.
</P>
<P>
The police chiefs of the area also agreed at the meeting to
intensify their efforts against common and organized crime in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
