<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Reports Trade Surplus of 468.1m U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Colombia registered a
trade surplus of 468.1 million U.S. dollars in the first six
months of this year as against a 1.822-billion-dollar deficit in
the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
A report published Saturday by the National Statistics
Administrative Department attributed the surplus to a 36 percent
contraction of imports caused by economic recession.
</P>
<P>
The imports of capital goods and building materials dropped by
41.6 percent in the period under review, followed by equipment and
transportation facilities with 35.7 percent, and raw materials
with 30.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports from the United States, Colombia's no. 1 trade partner,
dropped by 29.4 percent to 1.849 billion dollars. Imports from
Japan fell by 51.1 percent to 208.2 million dollars and from
Venezuela to 386.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Colombia's exports also dropped by 5.1
percent in the first six months of the year to 5.214 billion
dollars compared with 5.497 billion in the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Colombia starts to show a surplus in the current
account after six consecutive years of deficit that reached its
highest level in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
