<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> I Feel Attached to China: Madame Mongella </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Madame Gertrude Mongella,
best known as the Secretary General of the United Nations' Fourth
World Conference on Women, has got a nickname of "Mama Beijing"
from Tanzanians since the 1995 event held in the Chinese capital.
She readily accepted the name that showed their respect and
affection for her.
</P>
<P>
"I will never forget this experience that makes me feel more
attached to China," Mongella said in her office, which is
situated in a quiet garden-like courtyard on the west outskirts of
Tanzania's capital Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
"I first learned about China in the early 70s when the Chinese
helped us build the Tanzania-Zambia Railway," Mongella said in a
recent interview with Xinhua. "At that time I was a teacher and
visited the construction site with my students."
</P>
<P>
 An eight-time visitor to China, Mongella said she still wants
to go to Beijing, especially when the country will hold a grand
ceremony to mark its 50th anniversary on October 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
During the past 50 years, particularly in the past two decades,
the living standards of common Chinese people have remarkably
improved, she said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that China has made a big change and is more and more
open to the world. Although it's a developing country, it has a
lot of elements of developed countries, she added.
</P>
<P>
Two years after the Beijing conference, Mongella went to China
and found changes again. "New technology, new buildings, new
factories, and improvements in food processing, telecommunications
and transportation-- I saw it with my eyes," she said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980s, Mongella, who served as head of three different
ministries in Tanzania, and High Commissioner to India, visited,
among others, silk factories, fishing ponds, textile mills in a
lot of places in China, from the port city of Dalian in the
northeast to the southernmost province of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old woman, in a silk shirt printed with red flowers,
revealed cheerfully that the shirt was bought in Beijing. She has
a preference for the Chinese food that one eats not only "with
tongue" but also "with eyes."
</P>
<P>
The interview with Mongella in the inner room of her 20-square-
meter office, stuffed with computers, file holders and books, was
interrupted by telephone calls several times.
</P>
<P>
Although Mongella is quick to smile and give someone a
reassuring embrace, her slow, deliberate manner hides the quick
mind that picks up every body language signal-- a friendly tone of
voice or a mean glint in the eye.
</P>
<P>
"I founded Advocacy for Women in Africa (AWA) in 1996 after
Beijing," she said. The AWA is a non-governmental organization
that was a response to her own view that after the ending of the
women's conference, everyone must go home and do their homework.
</P>
<P>
The project, which has links with the United Nations,
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and women's organizations all
over the world, is dedicated to peace in African countries like
Burundi, Congo (K) and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
A member of OAU Women Committee for peace, Mongella realized
that unless the African continent is free from conflicts, the
Beijing Platform for Action could never be implemented. She hopes
to open new chapters all over Africa.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting upon the Fourth World Conference on Women hosted by
Beijing, she said, "Beijing did a wonderful job" as it brought 50,
000 people from so many nations together to discuss very critical
issues of humanity and facilitated exchanges between women and "
they felt as one."
</P>
<P>
"Even now everybody talks about Beijing. Sometimes when people
talk about the women issue, they say Beijing and Beijing," she
said.
</P>
<P>
"I also made a lot of good friends in China," she said, citing
Chen Muhua, the former vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of
the National People's Congress (NPC). She described Chen as a
brilliant, courageous, well-educated person capable of leadership.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that the Chinese women have enjoyed a highly
respected position in the past 50 years and fully taken part in
the country's development, saying that China would not have made
such achievements without the contribution of Chinese women.
</P>
<P>
Mongella said that women of China and Tanzania have a profound
friendship, but their exchanges could be further expanded. She
suggested that Chinese women come to make investments and hold
commodity exhibitions together with their Tanzanian sisters.
</P>
<P>
She also sees the possibility of establishing a China-Tanzania
women's association, which will provide a new form of co-operation
between women from both countries. She said only in this way could
women of the two nations enhance expertise exchanges in fields
such as medicine and science.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relationships, Mongella said that the political
and economic cooperation is firm. However, the ties can still be
strengthened through equal trade, she noted.
</P>
<P>
She said that Tanzania is a window on the Indian coast for
China to explore the market of Africa, and China can make good use
of Tanzania's ports to do business with landlocked African
countries. She also stressed people-to-people exchanges apart from
official relationship.
</P>
<P>
Mongella expressed the hope that China could open its market to
developing countries like Tanzania and transfer technologies to
them so as to boost their economic developments. At the same time,
she hopes China can play an important role in helping African
countries out of conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
