<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing reiterated that China will
stick to its policy of rejuvenating China by relying on science
and education when meeting with delegates attending an
international high-tech forum in Beijing Friday.
</P>
<P>
-- Children's choruses from 12 countries and regions held a
concert Saturday night to mark the beginning of the International
Children's Choir Festival-Beijing 1999. Chinese Vice-Premier Li
Lanqing attended the opening ceremony together with 700 teenage
singers.
</P>
<P>
-- Some 100 Chinese experts and leading officials attended a
forum here Saturday sponsored by three domestic research
institutions to discuss China's strategy for developing nuclear
power.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Daily
</P>
<P>
-- A new subway section in this Chinese capital will go into
test operation on September 28. The section, with a total length
of 13.5 km, is an artery line running under the Chang'an Avenue,
with 12 stations along the way.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing will set up 66 medical-aid posts on Tian'anmen
Square and major thoroughfares during mass parades to mark the
50th anniversary of the People's Republic on October 1.
</P>
<P>
China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- As the world lumbers towards the turn of the century, the
Year 2000 computer problem is becoming more and more noticeable.
</P>
<P>
Many will be surprised to learn that some issues related to the
problem, often referred to as the Y2K bug, have not been resolved.
</P>
