<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flooding in Venezuela Displaces Thousands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Flooding caused by heavy rains
in the last few days has rendered some 15,000 homeless and brought
about huge economic losses in northeastern Venezuela, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
They said the situation could worsen in the next week with more
rains whopping the country.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures, given by the Civil Defense, showed that
some 50,000 people have been affected by the rains and the number
of the displaced stood at 15,000 only in the eastern state of
Anzoategui.
</P>
<P>
The authorities lodged the displaced in the buildings of
several public schools and in a sports center of the state, where
they have been given light mattresses and blankets, medicines,
clothes and food.
</P>
<P>
The rains this week have caused the overflowing of the Aragua,
Querecual, and Neveri rivers in Anzoategui.
</P>
<P>
An Anzoategui state government spokesperson said that rain that
fell those days was 50 percent of what is expected of all the next
winter season.
</P>
<P>
The rains caused the rivers to topple the Gomez and Bergantin
bridges, two of the most important in Anzoategui, cutting the
state's communications with the central region.
</P>
<P>
The floods forced many residents to climb to the roofs of their
houses.
</P>
<P>
The authorities estimated the economic losses caused by the
rains at millions of U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
