<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Real Estate Sector Still in Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' real estate
sector remains in a slump as evidenced by the continued reluctance
of the banking sector to make new real estate investments or
increase its exposure to that sector.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest data revealed by the Central Bank of
the Philippines, the real estate exposure of the banking sector in
the second quarter of this year fell to 12.9 percent from the
first quarter level of 13.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said that the decline could be traced to a
combination of growth in the banks' total loan portfolio and a
decrease in real estate loans.
</P>
<P>
During the second quarter, the banking system's loan portfolio
grew by 12.2 billion pesos (310 million U.S. dollars), but the
actual real estate loan exposure of the banks declined, the
central bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the decrease in the banks' real estate loan
exposure was due to improved collection of outstanding real
estate loans or foreclosure of properties used as collateral.
</P>
<P>
Since the financial crisis started in 1997, Philippine banks
have been very cautious about the lending to real estate sector
and in investing in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The central bank then imposed a 20 percent ceiling on the
banks' exposure to the property sector to prevent financial risks.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian President Raises Conditions for Visit to Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori
will visit Chile if Chile agrees on the implementation of pending
clauses in the 1929 peace treaty, Foreign Minister Fernando de
Trazegnies said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Trazegnies said an invitation for a Fujimori visit to Chile is
in force and will come about when the dispute over the 1929 peace
treaty is resolved.
</P>
<P>
The treaty foresees that Chile will deliver a wharf, a customs
building and a railroad station to the southern Peruvian
department of Tacna.
</P>
<P>
Peru lost to Chile the locality of Arica, bordering with Tacna,
after a war between the countries from 1879 to 1883.
</P>
<P>
If Fujimori's visit is agreed on, it will be the first of a
Peruvian president to Chile in this century.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Peru and Chile are confident that the 1929
Peace Treaty's pending clauses will be fulfilled this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
