<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin will fly to Bishkek,
Kyrgyzstan, Tuesday to attend the summit of China, Kazakhstan,
Kyrgyzstan, Russia and Tajikistan, his spokesman said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Ekho Moskvy radio station, Dmitry
Yakushkin said the Bishkek meeting would be devoted to "border
issues concerning the five neighboring countries and the creation
of a zone of military security in the region. (Russia-Yeltsin-
Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The leader of an major Palestinian opposition group
arrived in Cairo on Saturday for a meeting with Palestine
Liberation Organization (PLO) Chairman Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Nayef Hawatmeh, secretary general of the Democratic Front for
the Liberation of Palestine (DFLP), is to lead his group's
delegation to the meeting with that of Fatah, led by Arafat, on
Sunday, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported. (Egypt-
Palestinians-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Nine people were shot dead in separate
incidents for no apparent reasons in a farm near KwaMashu north of
Durban in KwaZulu-Natal overnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
The killed included a three-year-old boy who was brought to
hospital after being shot but died upon arrival.
</P>
<P>
Two shacks in the area were burnt down and the occupants were
burnt beyond recognition.  (SAfrica-Killing Incidents)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Liberian Government said Saturday that the country
does not have the means to cope with the worsening refugee flood
issue from the fighting areas between government troops and rebels
and appealed to the international community for help.
</P>
<P>
Liberian Information Minister Joe Mulbah said that the United
Nations should give his country urgent food and medical aid to
help tide off the worsening humanitarian emergency in the northern
part of the country, according to reports reaching here today.
(Liberia-UN-Emergency)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South African Foreign Minister Nkosazana Zuma
left for Uganda and Rwanda Saturday for a new round of talks on
the long-running conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Zuma's latest peace mission may also include a stopover in the
Congo, her spokesman Vincent Hlongwane said.  (SAfrica-Rwamda-
Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia's former prime minister Sergei Stepashin on
Saturday refused to join two other former premiers in a new pro-
Kremlin, right-centrist political bloc.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, who was fired as prime minister earlier this month,
has been consulting with parties led by two other ex-premiers:
Viktor Chernomyrdin's Our Home is Russia and Sergei Kiriyenko's
New Force.  (Russia-Stepashin)  
</P>
