<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Sprinters Advance to 100m Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- American sprinter Marion Jones
took the first stride with the fastest time of the year in the
second round of the heats at the women's 100-meter dash of the
World Athletics Championships here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Competing in the steamy heat under the Spanish sunshine, Jones
clocked 10.76 seconds in the second round, bettering her own year'
s best of 10.80.
</P>
<P>
Only Florence Griffith-Joyner, Christine Arron, Merlene Ottey
and Jones, herself, have ever run faster.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Jones, who is going for four golds here, clocked 11.22
seconds in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
The defending champion, who has never exepriencing the taste of
defeat since the year 1997, is edging closer to Griffith-Joyner's
10.49 record for the distance.
</P>
<P>
She hinted after the heats that she may become the fastest
runner ever at the world championships. "I am not putting pressure
on myself by talking about times but if the fast times are needed,
here I'm ready to do them."
</P>
<P>
"These champinships are what it's all about. It's right here
and I'm right here. Nothing else really matters unless you can
make it count at a championships," she said.
</P>
<P>
Jones also qualified for Monday's long jump with a leap of 6.81
meters with her second attempt.
</P>
<P>
Two-times 200m European champion Christine Arron of France, who
hopes to make a slice of history by winning women's 100m and 200m
events here, also made semi-final in the women's 100m event with a
clocking of 11 seconds.
</P>
<P>
But her dream might be broken by the American sprinters
including Inger Miller, who was second fastest in the heats at 10.
86 seconds, a personal best for the joyful athlete.
</P>
<P>
"I knew I had this 100m in me, it was just a matter of time. I
have been popping all seasson and I was certain my personal best
would fall soon," she said, jumping up and down and laughing.
</P>
<P>
"This is an exceptionally fast track and I love the track
surface," she added.
</P>
<P>
Maurice Greene of the United States, the fastest men's runner,
had a easy step to defend his world title of the 100m dash at the
championships, clocking 9.91 seconds in heat five.
</P>
<P>
While in the women's long jump qualification, 1995 world
champion Fiona May of Italy produced the longest jump and the
second best of the year at 7.04 meters.
</P>
<P>
Defending world champion Russian Lyudmila Galkina leapt to the
second place at 6.88 meters while Brazilian Maureen Higa Maggi,
the season's leader with 7.26, was almost in trouble making the
final with a jump of 6.66 meters, 0.12 meters below the
qualification mark of 6.80 meters. However, this was good enough
to take her into Monday's final.
</P>
<P>
Greek Niki Xanthou, silver medalist in Athens, made a surprise
in the qualification, managing only 6.34 meters, 0.64 meters
shorter than her season best. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
