<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunter Wins Men's Shot Put Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- American C.T. Hunter won the men
's shot put at the 7th World Athletics Championships here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hunter, bronze medalist at the Athens championships in 1997,
registered 21.79 meters in his last efforts for the win.
</P>
<P>
Oliver-Sven Buder of Germany finished second in 21.42 meters
and Aleksandr Bagach of Ukraine third in 21.26.
</P>
<P>
American John Godina, gold medalist in the last two
championships, came a distance seventh by throwing 20.35 meters.
</P>
<P>
"How can you plan a win like that," said Hunter, who married
women's star runner Marion Jones last year.
</P>
<P>
Hunter had 21.09 meters in his fifth attempt, only second after
Buder's 21.42. But Bagach took the second position after throwing
21.26.
</P>
<P>
Hunter turned the last chance to victory with a throw of 21.79,
which finally earned him the gold.
</P>
<P>
"I knew I had it all to do on the last put and everything came
right for me. Basically I went after it. I gave it everthing I had!
maybe I had been trying too hard earlier on in the competition and
put too much pressure on myself," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The advantage with having only one throw left was it was an
all or nothing effort. I had nothing to lose and i certainly
gained here tonight."
</P>
<P>
He added: "John (Godina) has been awesome in the past, but
things change, you know. John will be back of course. A guy with
his sort of record can never be considered to be finished."
</P>
<P>
Buder said after winning the silver: "It was a great
competition! We had a great feeling out there tonight. I didn't
mind losing the gold medal, I was already satisfied with my
distance today. Silver is excellent for me." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
