<HEADLINE> Dragila Wins Women's Pole Vault with World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- American Stacy Dragila became
the brightest star on the opening day of the World Athletics
Championships when she won the women's paul vault with a world
record mark of 4.60 meters Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
The former world indoor champion, who had her personal best of
4.54 meters in an exhibition earlier this season, flied over the
standard in her last attempt, equalling the listed world record
set by Emma George of Australia last February.
</P>
<P>
George, who set world record 17 times, had a startling vault in
the debut-making event in which she failed three times at the 4.
35m mark.
</P>
<P>
The Australian injured her back at training in Switzerland
recently.
</P>
<P>
After clearing the bar at 4.15 meters, George passed at 4.25
and failed at 4.35.
</P>
<P>
Anzhela Balakhonova of Ukraine was second at 4.55 meters and
Tatiana Grigoryeva of Austria third at 4.45. 
</P>
