<DOCNO> XIE19990822.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Markov Wins First Gold, Jones and Hunter Shine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Ilya Markov captured
the first gold medal in the men's 20 kilometers walk while
Americans Marion Jones and her husband C.T. Hunter shone in the
first day's competition of the 7th World Athletics Championships
here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 100 meters defending champion Jones, who has unbeaten in
the track since 1997, clocked the year's fastest time of 10.76
seconds in the second round race this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Jones, the second fastest woman in the world after fellow
American Florence Griffith Joyner, also took a steady step toward
the goal of winning four gold medals in the championships after
advancing in the 200 meters and long jump.
</P>
<P>
But what she would celebrate most was the victory of her
husband Hunter, who won the men's shot put with a throw of 21.79
meters.
</P>
<P>
American John Godina, the 1995 and 1997 world champion,
finished a distance seventh with 20.35 meters.
</P>
<P>
Gonina was not the only star who fell in the opening day's
competition. Women's pole vault world record holder Emma George
of Australia also crashed out after three failures at 4.35 meters.
</P>
<P>
The event, which became an medal event for the first time in
the World Championships, was won by Stacy Dragila of the United
States with a world-record tying 4.60 meters.
</P>
<P>
Markov, who was disaqualified with five kilometers to go in the
Athens championships in 1997, pulled away from the leading pack in
the last two kilometers and took the win comfortably in one hour
23 minutes 34 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Olympic Champion Jefferson Perez of Ecuador finished second in
1:24:19 and defending champion Daniel Garcia of Mexico third in 1:
24:31.
</P>
<P>
Markov, the reigning European champion and silver medallist in
the 1996 Olympic Games, contributed his gold medal to his wife. "
Today is her birthday, this gold is for her," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's extremely hot, especially for a Russian but I'm in superb
form today. Before the competition, I know my top rival is Perez
because I lost to him in the 1996 Olympics. During walking, I'm
confident of winning the gold, " he said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian suffered a heartbreaking defeat in the 1997
championships where he held the lead most of the time but was
disqualified as the victory was in sight.
</P>
<P>
But this time he made no such mistake. "It was after 16km that
I knew the race was won by me. To be honest, I only came here for
the gold. The other colored medals would have been a
disappointment."
</P>
<P>
Perez, who was Ecuador's first Olympic gold medalist and the
youngest ever Olympic walks champion at 22, said: "The weather and
the walking course were not to my liking today. The 15km was the
crucial point in my race. I could only think about finishing the
race as I was already so tired."
</P>
<P>
He added: "I have not seen my family very much over the last
eight months. This is the price of training to reach the top.'
</P>
<P>
The bronze medalist Garcia said: "This performance will confirm
that I will continue to Sydney. There was nothing special today in
my race, but there weren't any major problems either. I have no
secrets in my training, I just focus entirely on myself and on my
goals."
</P>
<P>
Jones, who aims to win four gold medals in 100m, 200m, long
jump and 4x100m relay, bolted off the block to clock the fabulous
time of 10.76 seconds, beating the year-best time of 10.80, which
was set by herself.
</P>
<P>
"That's a fast track," Jones said. "I'm just excited. I'm not
putting pressure on myself by talking about times but if the fast
times are needed, here I'm ready to do them."
</P>
<P>
Men's 100m record holder and defending champion Maurice Greene
showed he is the undisputed fastest man in the world by clocking 9.
91 seconds in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
World 3,000m steeplechase record holder Bernard Barmasai of
Kenya also advanced with a pedestrian time of 8:16.50 in the first
round, a far cry from his world mark of 7:55.72. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
