<HEADLINE> ETA Supporters Slipped into Opening Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Seville security officials have
admitted that supporters of the Basque guerilla group ETA slipped
into Friday evening's opening ceremony of the World Athletics
Championships.
</P>
<P>
Nine people including two Basque activists dressing up as
official mascots were arrested at the stadium gala on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said the two activists -- a man and a woman --
entered the stadium as normal spectators and, once inside, had put
on perfect copies of the official mascot outfits which allowed
them to dance on a central stage in front of millions of
television viewers with a pro-ETA logo in English plastered on
their outsized costumes.
</P>
<P>
Three other protesters abseiled from one of the grandstands
with banners calling for the transfer of convicted ETA members to
jals in the Basque country.
</P>
<P>
And others handed out leaflets to members of the crowd and
journalists before being hauled away by police.
</P>
<P>
The head of Spain's national police Juan Cotina told National
Radio that checks on people entering the stadium were the
responsibility of the games' organisers.
</P>
<P>
"There was certainly a mistake on the part of the organisers
and the security forces who should have responded beefore the
incidents occurred," he said.
</P>
<P>
The organisers tightened security checks on people entering the
site of the championship Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
